ikely and it was practicable to work for a reunion with the Russian Jesuits, whose corporate existence had been recognized in Rome. In this Father Stone was successful. On 19 May 1803, having made his profession, he was declared provincial, and admitted others to their vows, for England, Ireland, and Maryland. On 29 September a novitiate was opened at [[Hodder Place]]. Rome, however, gave no public recognition of the restored order, though the pope privately expressed his pleasure. When the Bull of Restoration finally came (7 August 1814), the interpretation was added (2 December 1816), that it was to apply only where the secular government wished; in England, therefore, the Jesuits were to be regarded as still in their old position. The college had grown enormously since its transfer to England and the Jesuit missions had prospered steadily. Father Stone, notwithstanding his years, continued to act as college minister till 1827, when he finally retired to [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]]. Here the good news reached him (1829) that the English Jesuits had at last been formally recognized. He died in St Helens in 1834 and was buried in nearby Windlesham Abbey.<ref>{{cite book|title=Windleshaw Chantry and Cemetery|author=Rev Austin Powell|url=https://ia802604.us.archive.org/23/items/transactions02chesgoog/transactions02chesgoog.pdf| pages= 27-28|publisher= Transactions of the Historic Society of Lancashire and Cheshire for the year 1887|date=1887}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|}}\n\n==References==\n\n*Correspondence at Stonyhurst and elsewhere;\n*Gerard, ''Stonyhurst College'' (1894);\n*Foley, ''Records S. J.'', vii, 741;\n*Ward, ''The Dawn of the Catholic Revival'' (London, 1909);\n*____, ''The Eve of Catholic Emancipation'' (London, 1912).\n\n==External links==\n*[[s:Catholic Encyclopedia (1913)/Marmaduke Stone|''Catholic Encyclopedia'' article]]\n\n{{Catholic}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stone, Marmaduke}}\n[[C